Ecology. The type locality of Ahihi-Kina‘u is located on the southwest end of Maui first to be designated as a Natural Area Reserve in 1973 (
Fig. 1
). Covering a total area of 1,238 acres, the reserve includes 807 acres of submerged ecosystems as well as important anchialine habitats and lava fields from the last eruption of Haleakalā some 200 to 500 years ago. It is a key conservation site for anchialine pools in Hawaii and this habitat is not open to the public.
